english:
  title: Epitaph for An Gong, Lord of Heungnyeong, Former Magistrate of Gaeju under the Great Yuan
  author: Lee Gok
  language: eng
  text: |-
    When I was in the capital, I heard that Master Gyeonjae had fallen ill. Upon my return, I went to inquire after his health. Seeing me, he wept and said, "I shall not long remain in this world." Pointing to his son Jongyeon, he said, "If you would remember me, do not forget our boy." And entrusting me with his epitaph, he said, "I have nothing of which to boast in my life, yet having served four times as judge, whenever I found those who oppressed the common people or enslaved others, I set matters right. This alone is worthy of record."

    Hearing this, I was moved to sorrow and replied, "Does illness always prove fatal? Why do you speak with such urgency?" Alas, one might call him a gentleman who knew his destiny. When he had passed and the time came for burial, his younger brother Bo, being of the same year as I, came with the account of his deeds requesting this epitaph. Alas, I had once studied under him, and he himself commanded me—how could I refuse?

    His name was Chuk, and his courtesy name was Buji. He was from Heungnyeong of Bokju. His great-grandfather was Deukjae, and his grandfather Heeseo—both served as household administrators of their district. His father Seok achieved the highest degree but chose to withdraw from the world and never held office; thus both parents received posthumous honors. His mother was Madam An, Lady of Heungnyeong, daughter of Seonggi, the Deputy Commissioner of Military Equipment from the same region.

    From birth, he possessed keen intelligence and a natural aptitude for learning. He excelled in composition and passed the National Academy examination, then the civil service examination, receiving appointment as magistrate of Geumju. He was selected as inspector and reviser of the Records and Spring-Autumn Annals Institute. Again he passed the provincial examination and was appointed to the Censorate. In the year Gyehae, he ranked first in the provincial examination. In the year Gapja, at the court examination in the capital, he placed seventh in the third rank.

    By imperial decree, he was appointed magistrate of Gaeju. At that time, King Chungsuk had been held at the imperial court for four years. He said to his colleagues, "When the lord grieves, the minister is shamed; when the lord is shamed, the minister must die. Such is what we have learned." He thus submitted a memorial appealing to the king's innocence. The king praised this greatly and elevated him to Director of Music at the National Academy. Though the magistrate of Gaeju invited him with courtesy, the king wished to employ him and so he could not depart for his post. From Director of Music, he was transferred to the Four Directors' positions: Director of Law, Territory, Military Records, and Administration. He was promoted to Senior Counselor of the Right Bureau.

    When Crown Prince Yeongreung assumed power, he was dispatched to bring peace to Gangneung Province. He produced a collection of writings called "Eastern Ceramic Notes." He was appointed again as Judge of the Bureau of Ritual and Director of Law. When King Chungsuk returned to power, all those who had been favored by Yeongreung were dismissed. Some claimed he was the relative of those dismissed, and he was stripped of office. People said, "What one gains is by one's own merit; what one loses is because of kinship."

    Soon after, he was recalled as Minister of Law. But later, crossing the inner eunuchs who held influence, he was dismissed again. When Yeongreung returned to power, he was again appointed Minister of Law and Co-Examiner of the Civil Service. He selected thirty-three men, including the current Minister Yi Suil, and the age praised his selections. He was transferred from minister to Inspector General. Those of rank Director of Music and above regularly held concurrent office with the Institute, and though he became the head of the Censorate, he retained these positions. Many state memorials and imperial documents came from his brush.

    In the year Gyemil, with the rank of Associate Counselor, he went forth as magistrate of Sangju. Since Sangju bordered Bokju where Madam An, his mother, lived, he traveled back and forth to attend her with all filial care. In the spring of the year Gapsin, when the king began reforms, he was first consulted about choosing a prime minister and summoned as vice-minister of the Chancellery. Soon after, he was promoted to Gentleman of the Chancellery, and the following year given the additional rank of Associate Counselor. In the autumn of the year Jeonghai, he fell ill and was appointed Lord of Heungnyeong—it seems those in power did not favor we scholars, and so came this appointment.

    That winter, public outcry arose and he was restored to his former position. In the spring of the year Munja, his illness returned and he requested retirement. In the summer, on the first day of the sixth month, he was reappointed Lord of Heungnyeong, elevated to the rank of Commander of the Imperial Household. On the twenty-first day, his death was announced. The king commanded the appropriate officials to conduct his funeral rites with proper ceremony and to grant him posthumous gifts. He was given the posthumous name Moonjeong. All officials gathered for his burial, and his honor throughout life was complete and undiminished.

    On the eleventh day of the seventh month, he was interred on Daedeok Mountain. He lived sixty-seven years. His wife was Madam Mun, Lady of Gamcheon, daughter of Deputy Commissioner Gwi. They had two sons and one daughter. The eldest, Jongggi, was captain of the Imperial Horse Guard, but predeceased him. The second, Jongyeon, passed the examination and now serves as vice-minister of the Supply Bureau. The daughter married Captain Jeong Yanggang. He had two younger brothers: Bo, who passed the examination and in the year Eulyu at the capital was appointed administrator of Liaoyáng Province, and upon returning from official duties now serves as minister of the Right Bureau; and Jip, who passed the examination and now serves as rector of the National Academy.

    Their father died young, and he educated both younger brothers as though they were his own sons until they became men. Thus his brothers served him as they would have served their father. By the laws of our nation, when three sons pass the examination, their mother receives support for life from the state. This man and both his brothers achieved examination success and further passed the imperial examinations of the great Yuan—truly rare in the world. This too was the fruit of his teaching and nurture.

    His character was fair and impartial; he managed his household with diligence and frugality. His speech was direct and honest, without flattery. In office, he labored without weariness. Seeing goodness, he praised it without end, and thus gained much esteem. Seeing wrongdoing, he avoided it and stayed distant, and thus incurred little resentment. He called his dwelling place the "Hall of Carefulness," by which his intention may be understood.

    The epitaph says:
    Shall we say he did not live long?
    His years approached the seventh decade.
    Shall we say he did not rise high?
    His rank surpassed his peers.
    He had brothers and sons,
    Virtue and worthy fame.
    My words do not embellish—
    They merely mark his grave.
  footnotes:
    - The epitaph is written in the form of a traditional Korean cenotaph inscription. Lee Gok was both a personal student and later the official commissioned to write this memorial.
    - Gyeonjae ('Hall of Carefulness') was An Gong's self-chosen name, reflecting his character and values.
    - The reference to 'Yeongreung' (永陵) refers to Crown Prince Hyuk, later known as King Hyugjong.
    - The 'Eastern Ceramic Notes' (關東瓦注) was a significant literary work, suggesting An Gong's cultural accomplishments beyond his administrative duties.
